<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="dc1-sample" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>DC-1 Sample Outcomes</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 3 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  
  <page>
    <exercise>
        <introduction><p>Given the function <m>g(x,y)=\frac{y}{2x+3y}</m></p></introduction>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Find the first-order partial derivatives of <m>g(x,y)</m>.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the partial derivatives, use the quotient rule.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>\frac{\partial g}{\partial x} = \frac{-2y}{(2x+3y)^2}</m></p>
                <p><m>\frac{\partial g}{\partial y} = \frac{2x}{(2x+3y)^2}</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>To find the partial with respect to <m>x</m>, 
                treat <m>y</m> as a constant and apply the quotient rule:</p>
                <p><m>\frac{\partial g}{\partial x} = \frac{(2x+3y)(0) - y(2)}{(2x+3y)^2} 
                    = \frac{-2y}{(2x+3y)^2}</m></p>
                    <p>To find the partial with respect to <m>y</m>, treat <m>x</m> as a 
                        constant and apply the quotient rule:</p><p><m>\frac{\partial g}{\partial y} 
                            = \frac{(2x+3y)(1) - y(3)}{(2x+3y)^2} = \frac{2x}{(2x+3y)^2}</m></p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Find the second-order partial derivatives of <m>g(x,y)</m>.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the second-order partial derivatives, differentiate the first-order partial derivatives.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>\frac{\partial^2 g}{\partial x^2} = \frac{8y^2}{(2x+3y)^3}</m></p>
                <p><m>\frac{\partial^2 g}{\partial y^2} = \frac{8x^2}{(2x+3y)^3}</m></p>
                <p><m>\frac{\partial^2 g}{\partial x \partial y} = \frac{\partial^2 g}{\partial y \partial x} = \frac{-4x - 6y}{(2x+3y)^3}</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>To find the second-order partial derivative with respect to <m>x</m>, differentiate the first-order partial derivative with respect to <m>x</m> with respect to <m>x</m>:</p>
                <p><m>\frac{\partial^2 g}{\partial x^2} = \frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(\frac{-2y}{(2x+3y)^2}\right) = \frac{8y^2}{(2x+3y)^3}</m></p>
                <p>To find the second-order partial derivative with respect to <m>y</m>, differentiate the first-order partial derivative with respect to <m>y</m> with respect to <m>y</m>:</p>
                <p><m>\frac{\partial^2 g}{\partial y^2} = \frac{\partial}{\partial y}\left(\frac{2x}{(2x+3y)^2}\right) = \frac{8x^2}{(2x+3y)^3}</m></p>
                <p>To find the mixed partial derivatives, differentiate the first-order partial derivatives:</p>
                <p><m>\frac{\partial^2 g}{\partial x \partial y} = \frac{\partial}{\partial y}\left(\frac{-2y}{(2x+3y)^2}\right) = \frac{-4x - 6y}{(2x+3y)^3}</m></p>
                <p><m>\frac{\partial^2 g}{\partial y \partial x} = \frac{\∂}{\∂x}\left(\frac{2x}{(2x+3y)^2}\right) = \frac{-4x - 6y}{(2x+3y)^3}</m></p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Evaluate <m>g_{xyyx}(1,2)</m>.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Use the second-order partial derivative found earlier to find the third and fourth-order partial derivatives.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>g_{xyyx}(1,2) = -\frac{1}{32}</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>First we find the third and fourth-order partial derivatives:</p><p>Given that <m>g_{xy} = \frac{-4x - 6y}{(2x+3y)^3}</m>, 
                we can find the third-order partial derivative <m>g_{xyy}</m> by differentiating <m>g_{xy}</m> with respect to <m>y</m>:</p><p> This 
                    will give <m>g_{xyy} = \frac{\partial}{\partial y}\left(\frac{-4x - 6y}{(2x+3y)^3}\right)</m>. 
                Then we can find the fourth-order partial derivative <m>g_{xyyx}</m> by differentiating <m>g_{xyy}</m> with respect to <m>x</m>:</p>
                <p><m>g_{xyyx} = \frac{\partial}{\partial y}\left(\frac{\partial^2 g}{\partial x \partial y}\right) = \frac{\partial}{\partial y}\left(\frac{-4x - 6y}{(2x+3y)^3}\right)</m></p>
                <p>Substitute <m>x = 1</m> and <m>y = 2</m> into the expression for <m>g_{xyyx}</m>:</p>
                <p><m>g_{xyyx}(1,2) = \frac{-4(1) - 6(2)}{(2(1)+3(2))^3} = \frac{-16}{(8)^3} = \frac{-16}{512} = -\frac{1}{32}</m></p></solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction><p>Given the function <m>f(x,y)=4x^3y^2-2x^2y+5x</m></p></introduction>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Find the first-order partial derivatives <m>f_x</m> and <m>f_y</m>.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Use the power rule and the chain rule to differentiate.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>f_x = 12x^2y^2 - 4xy + 5</m></p><p><m>f_y = 8x^3y - 2x^2</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>To find <m>f_x</m>, differentiate <m>f(x,y)</m> with respect to <m>x</m>:</p>
                <p><m>f_x = \frac{\partial}{\partial x}(4x^3y^2 - 2x^2y + 5x) = 12x^2y^2 - 4xy + 5</m></p>
                <p>To find <m>f_y</m>, differentiate <m>f(x,y)</m> with respect to <m>y</m>:</p>
                <p><m>f_y = \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(4x^3y^2 - 2x^2y + 5x) = 8x^3y - 2x^2</m></p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Find the second-order partial derivatives <m>f_{xx}</m>, <m>f_{yy}, f_{yx}</m>, and <m>f_{xy}</m>.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Use the power rule and the chain rule to differentiate.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>f_{xx} = 24x^2y^2 - 4y</m></p><p><m>f_{yy} = 8x^3 - 4x^2</m></p><p><m>f_{xy} =f_{yx}= 24x^2y - 4x</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>To find <m>f_{xx}</m>, differentiate <m>f_x</m> with respect to <m>x</m>:</p>
                <p><m>f_{xx} = \frac{\partial}{\partial x}(12x^2y^2 - 4xy + 5) = 24x^2y^2 - 4y</m></p>
                <p>To find <m>f_{yy}</m>, differentiate <m>f_y</m> with respect to <m>y</m>:</p>
                <p><m>f_{yy} = \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(8x^3y - 2x^2) = 8x^3 - 4x^2</m></p>
                <p>To find <m>f_{xy}</m>, differentiate <m>f_x</m> with respect to <m>y</m>:</p>
                <p><m>f_{xy} = \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(12x^2y^2 - 4xy + 5) = 24x^2y - 4x</m></p></solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    </page>
</worksheet>
